04587nam a22005535i 9780822383390DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20022002ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223833907 a10.1515/97808223833902doi  a(DE-B1597)552776  a(OCoLC)191222209  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHC107.N72bC653 2002 7aBUS0230002bisacsh04a330.9747/3703221  aNW 27082rvk1 aBruegel, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFarm, Shop, Landing :bThe Rise of a Market Society in the Hudson Valley, 1780–1860 /cMartin Bruegel. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b7 b&w photos, 23 tables, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations, Tables, Figures, and Maps -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Everyday Life and the Making of Rural Development in the Hudson Valley -- t1 Exchange and the Creation of the Neighborhood in the Late Eighteenth Century -- t2 To Market, to Mill, to the Woods -- t3 Natural Resources and Economic Development -- t4 Farms Woven into the Landscape: Agricultural Developments, 1810–1850s -- t5 Country Shops and Factory Creeks, 1807–1850s -- t6 ‘‘Things, Not Thought’’: Wealth, Income, and Patterns of Consumption, 1800–1850s -- t7 The Culture of Public Life -- tConclusion: Labor, the Manor, and the Market -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the nineteenth century, when the word “capital” first found its way into the vocabulary of mid-Hudson Valley residents, the term irrevocably marked the profound change that had transformed the region from an inward-looking, rural community into a participant in an emerging market economy. In Farm, Shop, Landing Martin Bruegel turns his attention to the daily lives of merchants, artisans, and farmers who lived and worked along the Hudson River in the decades following the American Revolution to explain how the seeds of capitalism were spread on rural U.S. soil.Combining theoretical rigor with extensive archival research, Bruegel’s account diverges from other historiographies of nineteenth-century economic development. It challenges the assumption that the coexistence of long-distance trade, private property, and entrepreneurial activity lead to one inescapable outcome: a market economy either wholeheartedly embraced or entirely rejected by its members. When Bruegel tells the story of farmer William Coventry struggling in the face of bad harvests, widow Mary Livingston battling her tenants, blacksmith Samuel Fowks perfecting the cast-iron plough, and Hannah Bushnell sending her butter to market, Bruegel shows that the social conventions of a particular community, and the real struggles and hopes of individuals, actively mold the evolving economic order. Ultimately, then, Farm, Shop, Landing suggests that the process of modernization must be understood as the result of the simultaneous and often contentious interplay of social and economic spheres.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aIndustrializationzNew York (State)zColumbia County. 0aIndustrializationzNew York (State)zGreene County. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economic History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383390zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383390423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822383390/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_